00:04:07,920 --> 00:04:13,280
What was kind of your framework of way of doing things and way of building in cursor without a bunch of experience?

64
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:24,160
I think the separating factor from people who use cursor well and don't use cursor well is the way you communicate what you want the AI to do.

65
00:04:24,160 --> 00:04:29,759
And what I've kind of figured out is basically the smaller you can break down your problems,

66
00:04:29,759 --> 00:04:33,440
your challenges, your requests, the better your results will be.

67
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:38,000
So let's say I'm trying to build a feature around AI brain dumps, right?

68
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,600
What I would do is is I would try to break that feature down into the smallest building blocks possible.

69
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:51,120
So my first request would be, hey, can you build an input where a user can enter in an essay or a brain dump?

70
00:04:51,120 --> 00:04:59,600
It would do that and then I go, okay, next I want you to build a button that will eventually repurpose the content.

71
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:06,560
And they build the button and I go, okay, now I want you to command the AI model to take that essay and turn it into a tweet.

72
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:13,039
And while it seems like that would take much longer, you'll actually get done a lot more and a lot faster because you're not going to run into bugs that way.

73
00:05:13,039 --> 00:05:20,720
And a little hack there, if you actually have chat GPT up on the side, you can say, "Here's a feature I want to build.

74
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:25,520
Can you break it down into micro steps and then just take that output and put it into cursor?"

75
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:29,600
So, that really is the biggest key, breaking it down into micro steps for the AI.

